items.title: To my fellow visual humans, you might feel me when‚Ä¶
items.content_html:
@swissmiss

To my fellow visual humans, you might feel me when I say: I hate TVs. That black rectangle that most humans arrange their living space around. That‚Äôs why I am a big fan of projectors. They hide away. They are subtle. (The new short throw projector by VAVA is great!) But when you have a wall that is flooded with direct sun light, all day long, projectors don‚Äôt work. I researched alternatives and found Le Frame from Samsung. A TV that is mounted flush to the wall and looks like a big piece of art when not in use. The brain of the tv is stowed away underneath in the tv console (which by the way is by @castleryus). Le Frame was designed by fellow Swiss industrial designer @yvesbehar and I can wholeheartedly say I have never been more excited about a gadget. The entire product experience is excellent. (With the exception of opening the remote to put batteries in. I had to YouTube it to see if someone had some tips! And sure enough, a kind soul explained the trick!) The joy it brings me to change the art is unmatched. Creating a home that is visually pleasing is my happy place. And yes, I acknowledge, I am lucky I have the finances to do so. (Ps: This is not a sponsored post. I genuinely love sharing products I love. I have been doing so for 15+ over on my blog. Swiss-miss.com)

items.title: Today my son turned 11
items.content_html:
@swissmiss

Today my son turned 11. A few thoughts on the day: Photo 1: It sucks to have a birthday during a pandemic. Especially when you are a kid. Streamers outside your house telling everyone in the neighborhood it‚Äôs your birthday makes it a little better. Photo 2: Cats dig balloons. Who knew!? Video 3: Given the pandemic birthday nature, I wanted to create something special and decided to hang a gaggle of love notes above Tilo‚Äôs bed. Each of them describes something I love about him. Will he roll his eyes or approve? Photo 4: Success! It resonated. He had a *huge* smile on his face and said ‚Äúthis is sooo cool!‚Äù Photo 5: May this be his first and last pandemic birthday. Maybe it helps to know that 11, 22, 33, 44, 55, 66... are considered lucky birthdays in Switzerland. We call them ‚ÄúSchnapszahl birthdays‚Äù. Aka ‚ÄúSchnaps number‚Äù as in seeing double. I love you, Tilo!

items.title: Slow Tina, slow
items.content_html:
@swissmiss

Slow Tina, slow. These ski slope markers were seemingly talking to my subconscious these past few days. It‚Äôs my kids‚Äô winter break and I took three days off to go skiing upstate, in search of some normalcy and pursuit of joy. (My kids have been couped up at home for almost a full year now, remote schooling.) Besides being nervous on how this would all work in regards to Covid safety, I am in the middle of a work Tsunami, making it difficult to be fully present. I found myself waking up in the wee hours, mind racing, and trying to get a few hours of work in before everyone wakes up. I had entrepreneurial parents growing up and as a kid, didn‚Äôt understand why they would be talking about work or being on the phone with their staff during vacation. (No email or Slack back then!) I get it now. I wish Catamount, the ski area, would put Ram Dass‚Äôs words ‚ÄúBe Here Now‚Äù on the side of the slopes as well, just like the SLOW markers. I bet I am not the only one who could use the reminder. Being *fully* present, no matter what is happening in your life, is a practice. Some days I can do it. Some days I can‚Äôt. Here‚Äôs to learning and growing. Ps: The second photo is my little family, including ex-husband. We amicably divorced and love skiing together. This makes me happy.

items.title: ‚ÄúLife will break you
items.content_html:
@swissmiss

‚ÄúLife will break you. Nobody can protect you from that, and being alone won‚Äôt either, for solitude will also break you with its yearning. You have to love. You have to feel. It is the reason you are here on earth. You have to risk your heart. You are here to be swallowed up. And when it happens that you are broken, or betrayed, or left, or hurt, or death brushes too near, let yourself sit by an apple tree and listen to the apples falling all around you in heaps, wasting their sweetness. Tell yourself that you tasted as many as you could.‚Äù ‚Äï Louise Erdrich

items.title: This year had been tough for so many for so many r‚Ä¶
items.content_html:
@sohlae

This year had been tough for so many for so many reasons, but I‚Äôm trying to be grateful for the good. 2020 is the year I learned to know my worth, and it‚Äôs not just about getting paid fairly. My opinions and ideas deserve respect, and so do yours. As a woc I‚Äôve always been expected to be grateful for any opportunity, take what‚Äôs given to me without question, and stay quiet. That‚Äôs not only expected of woc, but anyone who doesn‚Äôt fit a very narrow idea of what a leader should look like. Fuck that. Don‚Äôt let anyone shut out your ideas because they think you‚Äôre not thin enough or rich enough or straight enough or white enough or man enough. That‚Äôs not me anymore. Thank you for all of your support. You lifted me up just when I was ready to give up and I hope I can share that energy with others in 2021. Cheers to a New Year and let‚Äôs keep pushing!

items.title: I remember when meant pound, not hashtag
items.content_html:
@sohlae

I remember when meant pound, not hashtag. Back when there were landlines and *69? So... I want to call this okay? Make sure you take care of the details: start with room temperature ingredients to create a stable emulsion, cream the butter and sugar until fluff-city, and stop the mixer to scrape down the paddle and the bowl. If you do all that this base vanilla batter can take on anything, from a few extra folds for mix-ins like chopped dates or blueberries, flavors like matcha or lemon zest, or swirls of cocoa and streusel like my black and white variation above! Head over to @food52 to learn my go-to, super tender, unfaltering recipe then take it off-script and make it all your own! Thanks to @emmalaperruque for the expert editing and @gabriellamm @fakattack and @wonbowoo for turning my tried ramblings into a video!
